EASTERN EQUINE ENCEPHALITIS, HORSE - MEXICO
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Wed, 24 Sep 1997
From: Sharon Rose <fasstudy@fas.org>
Source: OIE Disease Reports, Vol 10, No 42
Emergency report: Translation of a fax received on 23 October 1997 from
Dr. A.O. Flores Hern치ndez, Director General of Animal Health Department,
Secretariat for Agriculture, Animal Production and Rural Development
(SAGAR), Mexico City
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: end of August 1997.
Location No. of outbreaks
Hidalgotitl치n district, State of Veracruz 1
Isla district, State of Veracruz 1
Tierra Blanca district, State of Veracruz 1
Tlalixcoyan district, State of Veracruz 1
Tlacotalp치n district, State of Veracruz 1
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
susceptible cases deaths destroyed slaughtered
... 22 13 ... ...
Diagnosis:
The Emergency National Animal Health Plan (DINESA) is investigating cases
of neuropathy which occurred in equines in five district in the central and
southern parts of the State of Veracruz. A total of 27 serum samples and 4
complete blood samples were submitted.
On 7 October 1997, a virus identified as being similar to eastern equine
encephalomyelitis was found in 3 serum samples taken from equines in La
Caldera village, Tlacotalp치n district. These samples have been sent for
confirmation to laboratories in the United States of America (Centers for
Disease Control, Atlanta, and National Veterinary Services Laboratories,
Ames, Iowa).
Control measures during reporting period:
The control and eradication programme, initiated by DINESA in cooperation
with the delegation of the Secretariat for Agriculture in the State of
Veracruz and the animal health staff, includes an intensive vaccination
campaign involving 30,000 equines, particularly in and around the
outbreaks, and a plan for the control of mosquito vectors.
Quarantine of the affected region (ban on equine movements to the rest of
the country).
--
ProMED-mail
e-mail: <promed@usa.healthnet.org>
[Isolation of EEE virus from the blood of an equid, no less from the bloods
of three, is unusual. By the time a horse becomes ill (perhaps up to a
week after infection) the viremia usually has disappeared. We await
definitive identification of these isolates. - Mod.CHC]
